An Empirical Study of Conjugate Gradient
Preconditioners for Solving Symmetric Positive Deﬁnite
Systems of Linear Equations
Marc A. Tunnell & David F. Gleich
Abstract
Despite hundreds of papers on preconditioned linear systems of equations, there re-
mains a signiﬁcant lack of comprehensive performance benchmarks comparing various
preconditioners for solving symmetric positive deﬁnite (SPD) systems. In this paper,
we present a preliminary comparative study of 81 using a broad range of precondition-
ers. Speciﬁcally, we evaluate 14 widely used preconditoners across 62 conﬁgurations
to assess their relative performance against using no preconditioner. Our focus is on
preconditioners that are commonly used in practice, are available in major software
packages, and can be utilized as black-box tools without requiring signiﬁcant a priori
knowledge. Additionally, we compare these against a selection of classical methods.
Our initial results indicate that the Incomplete Cholesky preconditioner often pro-
vides the best performance among the black-box preconditioners tested, signiﬁcantly
reducing computational costs on many matrices. However, no single preconditioner is
consistently the best across matrices. This work is part of a long-term study, and we
plan to continue development to expand the scope of the benchmark and reﬁne our
analysis in ongoing work.
1 Introduction
Solving large and sparse linear systems of equations is a fundamental problem in scientiﬁc
computing, one that arises in applications across the scientiﬁc and engineering disciplines [1,
2]. In particular symmetric positive deﬁnite (SPD) systems arise in areas such as structural
analysis [3], ﬂuid dynamics [4], and machine learning [5]. The solution of these systems is
often accelerated by the use of preconditioners, which are auxiliary linear operators that are
used to transform the original system into a more easily solved system.
Iterative methods like Conjugate Gradient (CG) [2, 6–9] for SPD systems and Minimum
Residual (MINRES) [10] for indeﬁnite symmetric systems are widely used due to their scal-
ability and eﬃciency compared to direct methods [1, 2,8]. However, the convergence rate of
iterative solvers heavily depends on the condition number of the matrix [11]. To improve
the condition number, preconditioners are used to transform the original system into one
with more favorable spectral properties, thereby accelerating the rate of convergence as a
function of the number of iterations [1, 2,11,12].
Over the past decades, numerous preconditioners have been proposed, including classical
examples such as Jacobi and symmetric Jacobi scaling [1], and iterative methods such
1
as Truncated Neumann series [13], Successive Over-Relaxation (SOR) [2, 14], and Incom-
plete Factorizations [12,15–17]. In addition to these more classical methods, more advanced
preconditioners have been proposed, including multigrid methods [18], algebraic multigrid
(AMG) [19], and domain decomposition based methods [20].
Despite there being an abundance of research on novel preconditioners and reviews that
discuss their theoretical performance [12,21], there is no comprehensive performance bench-
mark that provides an empirical comparison of the performance of these preconditioners.
Most existing studies utilize a small set of matrices or focus on a limited set of precon-
ditioners [12, 21], drawing conclusions that may or may not generalize to a broader set of
problems.
In this study, we aim to address this gap by providing a thorough performance evaluation
of a wide range of preconditioners on 81 SPD matrices from the SuiteSparse Matrix Collec-
tion [22]. Our focus is on preconditioners that are widely used in practice, that are available
in large software packages, and may be utilized as a black-box without requiring signiﬁ-
cant a priori knowledge of the underlying properties of the system. We limit ourselves to
preconditioners of this type to ensure the relevance of this study to the broader scientiﬁc
community.
This study contributes to the literature by providing a comprehensive performance bench-
mark of a wide range of preconditioners on a large set of SPD matrices. Explicitly, our main
contributations are that we:
• conduct a comprehensive benchmark of 62 conﬁgurations across 14 preconditioners on
81 SPD matrices,
• compare the eﬀectiveness of these preconditioners against each other and against the
unpreconditioned case, providing insight into their relative performance both in aggre-
gate and across diﬀerent classes of matrices,
• analyze the convergence characteristics of CG with diﬀerent preconditioners, providing
empirical insight into its behavior, and
• discuss practical considerations for selecting an appropriate preconditioner based on
our empirical results.
The remainder of this paper is organized as follows. We provide necessary background
information in section 2. In section 3, we describe the iterative solvers used in this study.
Afterward, in section 4, we describe the matrices used in this study. In section 5, we describe
the preconditioners used in this study. In section 6, we describe the experimental setup used
to evaluate the performance of the preconditioners. In section 7, we present the results of
the performance evaluation, which is broken into two subsections: individual matrices in
?? and aggregate results in ??. Finally, in section 8, we provide a summary of the results,
discuss the ongoing nature of our benchmarking eﬀort, and discuss the implications of the
preliminary results given here.

3 Krylov Subspace Methods
In this preliminary study, we focus on Krylov subspace methods for solving large, sparse
linear systems of equations. Speciﬁcally, we utilize the Preconditioned Conjugate Gradient
(PCG) method for SPD systems. We recognize that the performance of preconditioners may
be diﬀerent when applied with diﬀerent solvers; therefore, in future work, we will expand
our analysis to include Preconditioned Minimum Residual (PMR) method.
3.1 Preconditioned Conjugate Gradient
The PCG method is an eﬃcient iterative solver for SPD systems and is known for its scala-
bility and eﬃciency [2,6]. The convergence rate of the PCG method, like all Krylov methods,
is heavily dependent on the condition number of the matrix, and preconditioners are used to
improve the condition number of the system and accelerate the rate of convergence [1,2,11].
The PCG method can be viewed as a process that minmizes the quadratic function

3.2 Preconditioned Minimum Residual Method
A future extension of this study will include the Preconditioned Minimum Residual (PMR)
method, which seeks to minimize the residual of the system rather than the quadratic func-
tion over a Krylov subspace.
4 Systems of Linear Equations
In this section, we describe the selection of symmetric positive deﬁnite matrices used in
our study and discuss the graph-Laplacian matrices that we plan to include in a future
extension of this study. Our goal is to evaluate the performance of various preconditioners
on large-scale SPD systems that are representative of real-world problems.
4.1 Matrix Ordering
The ordering of a sparsse matrix is well known to be crucial for the performance of a large
number of preconditioners [1, 12]. In the symmetric case, the rows and columns of the
matrix must be permuted in the same way to preserve the symmetry of the matrix, so we
only consider symmetric reorderings in this study. In the context of direct solvers such as
Gaussian elimination or those preconditioners that compute an incomplete factorization,
the ordering of the matrix can have a signiﬁcant impact on the ﬁll-in and the quality of
the factorization [12, 25]. In this preliminary study, we currently only consider the natural
ordering of the matrices, but we will include a number of symmetric orderings in a future
expansion.
We denote the permutation matrix of a given ordering as P , where P AP
T
is the permuted
matrix. In the natural ordering case, P is the identity matrix.
Natural The natural ordering of a matrix is the order in which it is obtained from the
application that generated it. This serves as a baseline for comparison with other ordering
strategies.
6
Reverse Cuthill-McKee The Reverse Cuthill-McKee (RCM) algorithm was originally
proposed for reducing the bandwidth of a matrix [26]. By minimizing the bandwidth of
the matric, RCM aims to cluster the non-zero elements closer to the diagonal and has been
shown in practice to reduce the ﬁll-in of the matrix during factorization [27].
The RCM algorithm is a graph-based algorithm that traverses the graph of the matrix in
a breadth-ﬁrst search manner, starting from a vertex with minimal degree. Each node is
numbered in the order that they are visited and the numbering is reversed at the end of the
algorithm to give the ﬁnal ordering.
We utilize the SymRCM package in Julia to compute the RCM ordering of the matrices.
Symmetric Approximate Minimum Degree The Symmetric Approximate Minimum
Degree (SYMAMD) ordering is an approximate version of the minimum degree algorithm
that is designed to preserve the symmetry of the matrix [28]. SYMAMD is a greedy heuristic-
based algorithm that seeks to minimize the ﬁll-in of a cholesky factorization of a sparse
matrix [27]. We utilize the AMD package in Julia [29].
Nested Dissection Nested Dissection is a divide-and-conquer algorithm that recursively
partitions the graph of the matrix into two subgraphs [30]. It aims to minimize ﬁll-in by
identifying separators that divide the graph into smaller, roughly equal-sized subgraphs. We
utilize the dissect function in MATLAB to compute the nested dissection ordering of the
matrices [31].
Future Work In future iterations of this study, we will include the symmetric orderings
described above to evaluate the impact of the ordering on the performance of the precondi-
tioners.
Even without a preconditioner, the ordering of the matrix may have an impact on the
convergence of the solver because the ordering is applied prior to symmetric Jacobi Scaling.
4.2 Symmetric Positive Deﬁnite Matrices
We utilize matrices from the SuiteSparse Matrix Collection [22], a widely recognized reposi-
tory of sparse matrix benchmarks that are representative of real-world problems. To ensure
our study focuses on large-scale and practically relevant problems, we ﬁlter matrices based
on the following criteria:
• Matrix Dimension: Only matrices of dimension n ≥ 10,000 are considered. This
7
ensures that the matrices are suﬃciently large to reﬂect computational challenges en-
countered in real-world applications.
• Symmetric Positive Deﬁnite: We consider only those matrices that are real-valued
and symmetric positive deﬁnite in this study.
• Convergence without Preconditioning: The unpreconditioned Conjugate Gradi-
ent method should converge within 10 ·n iterations, where n is the matrix dimension.
This allows us to compare the relative performance of preconditioners in aggregate
against the unpreconditioned case.
By limiting our study to a test set of matrices that ﬁt these criteria, we ensure that we are
evaluating preconditioners on those matrices that present a computational challenge that
is typical in large-scale scientiﬁc and engineering problems. Additionally, requiring that
the unpreconditioned CG method converges within a reasonable number iterations enables
us to compare the relative performance of the preconditioners both in aggregate and on a
per-matrix basis.
Matrix Characteristics The selected matrices come from a diverse set of applications,
including structural analysis, ﬂuid dynamics, and optimization problems. These matrices
comprise a wide range of sizes and structures, reﬂecting the diversity of problems encoun-
tered in practice. This diversity allows us to evaluate the robustness and eﬀectiveness of
preconditioners across a broad spectrum of real-world problems.

4.3 Graph-Laplacian Matrices
In future iterations of this study, we will include undirected graphs by constructing their
corresponding graph-Laplacian matrix. These matrices are representative of problems in
graph theory [32], network analysis [33], and numerical simulations [34]. Graph-Laplacian
matrices are symmetric and diagonally dominant but are unique from general SPD matrices
and can present a challenge for iterative solvers and preconditioners.
Deﬁnition and Properties Given an undirected graph G = (V, E) with n vertices in
vertex set V and m edges in edge set E, the graph-Laplacian matrix L ∈ R

matrix is guaranteed be positive semi-deﬁnite by is not positive deﬁnite, meaning that at
least one eigenvalue is zero [35]. This property can present a challenge for iterative solvers
(e.g., CG, which assumes positive deﬁniteness) and preconditioners, as the matrix is not
strictly positive deﬁnite. The multiplicity of the zero eigenvalue, that is the nullspace of L,
is equal to the number of connected components in the graph [35].
These matrices pose a challenge for iterative solvers and preconditioners due to their spectral
properties, such as the presence of a zero eigenvalue and the structure of the nullspace [35].
We explore preconditioners that exploit the structure of the graph-Laplacian matrix and
compare them to more general preconditioners to understand their relative performance on
these matrices.
In an extension of this study, we will generate graph-Laplacian matrices from a diverse set
of undirected graphs and evaluate the performance of preconditioners on these matrices.

5 Preconditioners
In this section, we describe the preconditioners that are evaluated in this preliminary study.
Preconditioners are leveraged to improve the conditioning of the system, therby accelerating
the convergence of the solver [1, 2, 12].
10
We focus on preconditioners that are widely used in practice, available in major software
packages, and can be utilized as black-box tools without requiring extensive a priori knowl-
edge of the system. Our selection includes both classical methods and more advanced tech-
niques to provide a comprehensive evaluation.
These preconditioners include:
• Classical Methods: Traditional methods such as Gauss-Seidel and Successive Over-
Relaxation (SOR) [1], which are simple to implement and serve as a baseline for more
advanced preconditioners. The discussion on this class of preconditioners is provided
in subsection 5.1.
• Sparse Approximate Inverse: Techniques that construct an explicit approximation
of the inverse of the matrix in a sparse format [39–41], enabling eﬃcient application
during iterations. We discuss these methods in subsection 5.2.
• Incomplete Factorizations: Methods like Incomplete Cholesky and Incomplete LU
factorization [7, 15–17, 42–45], which approximate the original matrix by a factoriza-
tion that is computationally less expensive to apply. We discuss these methods in
subsection 5.3.
• Algebraic Multigrid (AMG): Advanced methods such as Ruge-Stuben AMG and
Smoothed Aggregation AMG [19, 21], which are provably eﬀective for some classes of
problems and can mostly be used as a black-box tool. We discuss these methods in
subsection 5.4.
• Graph-Laplacian Preconditioners: Specialized preconditioners designed for prob-
lems arising from symmetric graphs [19], including combinatorial multigrid and sparse
Cholesky approaches [46–48]. We discuss these methods in ??.
In the following subsections, we provide an overview of each preconditioner category, dis-
cussing their theoretical foundations, implementation considerations, and the expected com-
putational costs associated with their use.
5.1 Classical Methods
Classical iterative methods serve as the foundation of numerical linear algebra. Although
they are not as eﬃcient as more modern solvers, they are simple and still ﬁnd use in prac-
tice [1,2].
In the following, we describe the classical iterative methods, highlighting their connection to
matrix splitting techniques where relevant and their role as preconditioners.
11

5.3 Incomplete Factorizations
Incomplete factorizations are a class of preconditioners that approximate the factorization of
a matrix A in a sparse format, enabling eﬃcient application during iterative methods [1,12].
The sparsity of the incomplete factors are preserved by dropping some entries from the
20
factorization, which can lead to a signiﬁcant reduction in the computational cost of applying
the preconditioner. These are well-known to be eﬀective preconditioners [12], are widely
used in practice, and are available in many major software packages.
Next we desribe the Incomplete LU Factorization (ILU) and Incomplete Cholesky Factor-
ization (IC) preconditioners that we consider in our study.
5.3.1 MATLAB: Incomplete Cholesky
The IC factorization approximates the exact Cholesky factorization of an SPD matrix A ∈
R
n×n
by computing a sparse lower triangular matrix F such that:
A ≈ F F
⊺
.
The IC factorization retains only selected non-zero entries of the Cholesky factor along some
sparsity pattern. This sparsity pattern may be deﬁned by the structure of the matrix itself,
by some power of the matrix, or by some other criteria. The primary goal with any of these
criteria is to produce a factorization that is computationally less espensive to apply while
capturing the essential features of the original matrix [1,15].
The IC factorization supplied by MATLAB allows for either an ILU(0) variant or one that is
based solely on thresholding. In the case of the ILU(0) variant, the factorization is computed
without ﬁll-in along only the sparsity pattern of A. In the case of the threshold variant,
any amount of ﬁll-in is allowed provided that the entries are greater in magnitude than the
threshold.
The IC preconditioner is applied by solving triangular systems involving L and its transpose.
Given a residual vector r, the preconditioned residual is computed as:

5.3.3 SuperLU: Incomplete LU Factorization
For nonsymmetric or indeﬁnite matrices, the Incomplete LU (ILU) factorization is used. ILU

5.3.5 Theoretical Considerations
Incomplete factorization preconditioners aims to approximate the factors of the original
matrix while keeping the factors sparse. Their eﬀectiveness depends on a number of variables,
including the ﬁll-in level, the sparsity pattern, and the properties of the original matrix.
Additionally, they are well known to be highly dependent on the ordering of the matrix, which
can signiﬁcantly impact the eﬀectiveness of the preconditioner [1, 12]. For ill-conditioned
matrices, modiﬁed versions of the incomplete factorizations can be used to improve the
numerical stability of the preconditioner [51].
5.3.6 Computational Cost
The computational cost of applying the incomplete factorization is equal to the number of
non-zero values in each factor that is inverted. In the IC and MIC cases, this is two times
the number of non-zero values in the lower triangular factor. In the ILU case, this is equal
to the number of non-zero values in the lower and upper triangular factors.
5.4 Algebraic Multigrid
Algebraic Multigrid (AMG) methods are an advanced class of iterative methods that are
designed to solve large and sparse linear systems eﬃciently. These methods work by con-
structing a hierarchy of coarser and coarser grids that approximate the original problem,
allowing for the solution to be computed at diﬀerent levels of resolution [53]. Unlike ge-
ometric multigrid methods, which we do not consider in this study, AMG constructs the
hierarchy based on the matrix itself, making it more general and applicable to a wider range
of problems [1,19, 21, 53].
AMG is particularly eﬀective for elliptic PDEs, where the matrix is symmetric and positive
deﬁnite, and the problem is discretized on a structured or unstructured grid. For these types
of problms, they are known to achieve optimal or nearly-optimal convergence rates [19, 53].
In this study, we focus on the Ruge-Stuben AMG method and the Smoothed Aggregation
AMG method, which are two popular AMG methods that are widely used in practice [54].
We utilize the PyAMG library [54] to construct the AMG preconditioners.

6 Experimental Setup
In this section, we describe the experimental setup used to evaluate the performance of the
black-box preconditioners on a set of sparse matrices. We count the cost of solving a linear
system as the number of iterations times the amount of work expended in each iteration. For
the Control, or no preconditioner, we count the cost as the number of iterations times the
number of non-zero values in the matrix. For a preconditioned system, the cost per iteration
is the number of non-zero values in matrix plus the work expended by the preconditioner.

that is in focus is given in red and all other preconditioners are shown in gray. We deﬁne
a preconditioner group as all conﬁgurations that were tested for a single preconditioner on
that matrix. For some preconditioners, we group multiple conﬁgurations together—such as
grouping all conﬁgurations of the Incomplete Cholesky and Modiﬁed Incomplete Cholesky
preconditioners together.
These graphs do not include the time to generate a preconditioner, which may be a signiﬁcant
factor in the overall computational cost of the preconditioner.

for each matrix. For each matrix, all conﬁgurations are tested, and the performance proﬁle
is computed based on the optimal conﬁguration for that speciﬁc matrix.

8 Conclusion
In this preliminary study, we have presented a strong performance evaluation of various
preconditioners for solving large-scale symmetric positive deﬁnite (SPD) linear systems using
Conjugate Gradient. Focusing on 14 widely use preconditioners across 62 conﬁgurations, we
assess their relative performance against the unpreconditioned case on 81 SPD matrices from
the SuiteSparse Matrix Collection.
Our initial results indicate that the incomplete Cholesky preconditioner loften provides the
best performance among the black-box preconditioners tested, signiﬁcantly reducing compu-
tational costs on many matrices. However, no single preconditioner consistently outperforms
others across all matrices, underscoring the importance of selecting an appropriate precon-
ditioner based on the speciﬁc characterists of the matrix at hand. Classical methods like
Gauss-Seidel and Successive Over-Relaxation were generall less eﬀective, leading to poor
cases in all instances. This was not entirely true for their symmetric counterparts, which led
to convergence, but were not as eﬀective as many of the other preconditioners.
The algebraic multigrid preconditioners, such as Ruge-Stuben and Smoothed Aggregation,
showed promising results, especially on the matrices not coming from the structural problem
class.
This study is part of an ongoing eﬀort to provide a comprehensive benchmark of precon-
ditioners for SPD systems. In future work, we plan to expand our analysis in several key
areas:
• Inclusion of Matrix Orderings: We intend to investigate the impact of matrix
ordering on the performance of preconditioners by incorporating symmetric reorderings
such as Reverse Cuthill-McKee, Symmetric Approximate Minimum Degree, and Nested
Dissection. Given that matrix ordering can signiﬁcantly aﬀect the ﬁll-in and quality of
incomplete factorizations, this extension will provide deeper insights into the practical
application of preconditioners.
• Expansion of Preconditioner Types: Additional preconditioners, including do-
main decomposition methods and additional advanced algebraic multigrid techniques,
will be evaluated. By broadening the scope of preconditioners tested, we aim to identify
strategies that may oﬀer better performance for speciﬁc problem classes.
• Graph-Laplacian Matrices: We plan to include graph-Laplacian matrices in our
test set to assess the eﬀectiveness of preconditioners on problems with unique spectral
properties. These matrices pose particular challenges due to their positive semi-deﬁnite
nature and the presence of zero eigenvalues.
• Alternative Iterative Solvers: While this study focused on the PCG method for
SPD systems, we recognize that the choice of iterative solver can inﬂuence the eﬀec-
tiveness of preconditioners. Future work will include the Preconditioned Minimum
32
Residual method to evaluate preconditioner performance on indeﬁnite symmetric sys-
tems.
By addressing these areas, we aim to provide a more comprehensive understanding of how
these factors inﬂuence the performance of preconditioners in practical settings. This ongo-
ing study contributes to the literature by taking steps towards ﬁlling the gap in empirical
benchmarks for SPD systems.
